1 instruction in the early grades from a teacher who is skilled in teaching the
2 foundational components of reading, including phonemic awareness, phonics,
3 fluency, vocabulary, and comprehension. Students who require intensive
4 supplemental instruction tailored to the unique difficulties encountered shall be
5 provided those additional supports by an appropriately trained education
6 professional.
7 (b) Foundation for literacy.
8 (1) The Agency of Education, in collaboration with the State Board of
9 Education, the Agency of Human Services, higher education, literacy
10 organizations, and others, shall develop a plan for establishing a
11 comprehensive system of services for early education in public schools that
12 offer instruction in grades kindergarten through grade three to ensure that all
13 students learn to read by the end of the third grade. The plan shall be updated
14 at least once every five years following its initial submission in 1998.
15 (2) Approved independent schools that are eligible to receive public
16 tuition shall develop a grade-level appropriate school literacy plan that is
17 informed by student needs and assessment data. The plan may include
18 identification of a literacy vision, goals, and priorities and shall address the
19 following topics:
20 (A) measures and indicators;
